  "prompt": "What is the difference between shear stress and shear strain?",
  "response": "The key difference between shear stress and shear strain lies in **what they measure and how they relate to deformation:**\n\n*   **Shear Stress:**\n    *   **What it measures:** Shear stress is a measure of the **force per unit area** acting parallel to a surface. This force is caused by external forces trying to slide or deform the material.\n    *   **Cause or Effect:** It's the **cause** of deformation. It represents the internal resistance of a material to an external force trying to make it deform angularly.\n    *   **Units:** Pascals (Pa) or psi (pounds per square inch). (Force/Area)\n    *   **Concept:** Imagine a book lying flat on a table. If you push horizontally on the top cover, you're applying a shear force. The shear stress is the force you're applying divided by the area of the book cover.\n\n*   **Shear Strain:**\n    *   **What it measures:** Shear strain is a measure of the **deformation** of a material due to shear stress. It's the change in angle (usually a very small angle) caused by the applied shear stress.\n    *   **Cause or Effect:** It's the **effect** of shear stress. It quantifies how much the material has deformed angularly.\n    *   **Units:** Dimensionless (it's a ratio of lengths, or an angle in radians).  It is the ratio of the change in length to the original length, measured perpendicularly to the force.\n    *   **Concept:** In the book example, shear strain is the angle by which the sides of the book are tilted due to your pushing force.\n\n**Analogy:**\n\nThink of stress and strain in general terms:\n\n*   **Stress is the effort.** It's what you *apply* to the material.  It's like pushing on something.\n*   **Strain is the result.**  It's what happens to the material *because* of the effort.  It's like the material deforming or stretching.\n\n**Relationship:**\n\nShear stress and shear strain are related by a material property called the **shear modulus (G)**. This is analogous to Young's modulus (E) for tensile stress and strain.\n\nThe relationship is:\n\n```\nShear Stress = Shear Modulus * Shear Strain\n\u03c4 = G * \u03b3\n```\n\nWhere:\n\n*   \u03c4 (tau) = Shear stress\n*   G = Shear modulus (a property of the material indicating its resistance to shear deformation)\n*   \u03b3 (gamma) = Shear strain\n\n**In Summary:**\n\n| Feature          | Shear Stress                                     | Shear Strain                                          |\n|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|\n| **Definition**    | Force per unit area acting parallel to a surface | Deformation (change in angle) due to shear stress       |\n| **Cause/Effect**  | Cause (applied force)                              | Effect (deformation)                                  |\n| **Units**         | Pascals (Pa) or psi                               | Dimensionless (radians)                              |\n| **Material Prop** | Related to strain via Shear Modulus (G)         |  Related to stress through Shear Modulus (G)           |\n",
